00:30:55,367 --> 00:30:57,700
We could ride our bikes.

764
00:30:57,733 --> 00:30:59,800
So you probably..

765
00:30:59,833 --> 00:31:01,400
...shared each other's toys?

766
00:31:02,433 --> 00:31:04,833
Maybe even coats..

767
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:06,800
...gloves, boots?

768
00:31:08,467 --> 00:31:11,367
Andy would never
let me wear his boots.

769
00:31:11,400 --> 00:31:13,433
‐ Kind of too small, anyway.
‐ Oh.

770
00:31:13,467 --> 00:31:16,600
Remember when you were
trying to take them off?

771
00:31:16,633 --> 00:31:18,600
Right.

772
00:31:18,633 --> 00:31:20,233
So if he never
let you wear his boots

773
00:31:20,267 --> 00:31:22,167
then how come
you were wearing them

774
00:31:22,200 --> 00:31:23,767
when the paramedics
brought you in here?

775
00:31:25,833 --> 00:31:28,200
'Cause we had a bet and I won.

776
00:31:28,700 --> 00:31:29,800
A bet?

777
00:31:29,833 --> 00:31:31,300
To see who
could ride faster

778
00:31:31,333 --> 00:31:34,600
from his house
to the park, and I won.

779
00:31:34,633 --> 00:31:36,833
And whoever won
got to wear the boots, right?

780
00:31:36,867 --> 00:31:39,733
Yeah, but he
wouldn't give them to me.

781
00:31:39,767 --> 00:31:41,667
I rode faster
and he knew it.

782
00:31:41,700 --> 00:31:43,300
He wasn't being fair.

783
00:31:46,867 --> 00:31:48,267
Are these yours or Andy's?

784
00:31:48,300 --> 00:31:50,300
Neither.
They're my dad's.

785
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:55,100
Wilson, did you
put these into a gun?

786
00:31:55,133 --> 00:31:56,667
No. Those are extras.

787
00:31:56,700 --> 00:31:58,533
I already
had some in the gun.

788
00:32:02,200 --> 00:32:04,167
And when Andy
didn't give you the boots..

789
00:32:06,467 --> 00:32:08,300
...you pointed the gun at him?

790
00:32:14,133 --> 00:32:15,600
And you shot him?

791
00:32:15,633 --> 00:32:16,867
Not to hurt him or anything.

792
00:32:16,900 --> 00:32:19,133
Just to scare him.

793
00:32:19,167 --> 00:32:22,367
We had a bet and I won,
it was fair and square.

794
00:32:25,233 --> 00:32:29,500
You do know,
that you hurt him now, right?

795
00:32:29,533 --> 00:32:32,533
Look, all I meant
was to get the boots.

796
00:32:32,567 --> 00:32:35,300
You can't go back
on a bet, that's not right.

797
00:32:35,333 --> 00:32:37,367
Andy knows that.

798
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:39,233
What did you do
with the gun, Wilson?

799
00:32:39,267 --> 00:32:42,267
I dropped it down a drainpipe
when I got on my bike.

800
00:32:42,300 --> 00:32:43,700
See, the thing is,
none of this would have happened

801
00:32:43,733 --> 00:32:45,400
if that car hadn't hit me.

802
00:32:51,567 --> 00:32:53,500
You'll let me know
when my parents get here, right?

803
00:32:55,267 --> 00:32:58,733
Yeah, Wilson, I'll let you know.

804
00:32:58,767 --> 00:33:01,767
Oh, Nurse Hathaway?

805
00:33:01,800 --> 00:33:04,233
Can you please not tell
my dad I threw his gun away.

806
00:33:04,267 --> 00:33:06,367
He'll get really mad.

807
00:33:14,433 --> 00:33:15,867
So you're actually telling me
that he could go home today.

808
00:33:15,900 --> 00:33:17,333
Yeah, we don't have
prisons for eight‐year‐olds.

809
00:33:17,367 --> 00:33:18,500
I'm not talking
prison, I'm talking

810
00:33:18,533 --> 00:33:20,167
juvenile hall, detention center.

811
00:33:20,200 --> 00:33:22,333
Not for kids under ten.

812
00:33:22,367 --> 00:33:24,767
Can an eight‐year‐old
even understand his rights?

813
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:26,367
Or the consequences
of his actions?

814
00:33:26,400 --> 00:33:27,667
Well, of course he can.

815
00:33:27,700 --> 00:33:29,667
He shot Andy so he could
get the boots, right?

816
00:33:29,700 --> 00:33:31,367
He wanted to scare the boy.

817
00:33:31,400 --> 00:33:33,167
His intent might have been
just that, not to kill.

818
00:33:33,200 --> 00:33:35,133
But he did kill him!

819
00:33:35,167 --> 00:33:36,233
I mean doesn't that
count for something?

820
00:33:36,267 --> 00:33:37,267
Yeah, but what?

821
00:33:37,300 --> 00:33:38,867
Murder two, manslaughter?

822
00:33:38,900 --> 00:33:40,300
The kid is eight years old.

823
00:33:40,333 --> 00:33:42,367
Isn't it up to
the state attorney?

824
00:33:42,400 --> 00:33:44,233
Yes, but he's
got to be assessed

825
00:33:44,267 --> 00:33:45,733
he has to have
a psych evaluation.

826
00:33:45,767 --> 00:33:47,567
And social services
has to determine

827
00:33:47,600 --> 00:33:49,633
whether he can differentiate
between right and wrong.

828
00:33:49,667 --> 00:33:50,867
Of course he can.

829
00:33:50,900 --> 00:33:52,100
Why would he make up a story

830
00:33:52,133 --> 00:33:53,500
about the man chasing them?

831
00:33:53,533 --> 00:33:55,833
Does he have any awareness
of what he's done?

832
00:33:55,867 --> 00:33:57,333
Has he shown any remorse?

833
00:33:57,367 --> 00:33:59,333
Yeah, he's sorry
he tossed the gun.

834
00:33:59,367 --> 00:34:00,600
Afraid his father's
gonna get mad at him.

835
00:34:00,633 --> 00:34:03,467
Does that count as remorse?

836
00:34:03,500 --> 00:34:07,433
You are telling me the police,
the courts, psych

837
00:34:07,467 --> 00:34:11,267
social services, nobody knows
what to do with Wilson Geary?

838
00:34:11,300 --> 00:34:13,133
Pretty much.

839
00:34:13,167 --> 00:34:14,300
What a mess.

840
00:34:16,867 --> 00:34:18,300
Anything else
you want me to do?

841
00:34:18,333 --> 00:34:19,700
Not right now.

842
00:34:19,733 --> 00:34:20,767
I'll put her things in here.

843
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:22,733
Thanks, Chuny.

844
00:34:22,767 --> 00:34:24,167
I'll go talk to the family.

845
00:34:33,467 --> 00:34:36,567
Apparently, she was
sucking on a hard candy

846
00:34:36,600 --> 00:34:38,433
and it lodged in her windpipe.

847
00:34:38,467 --> 00:34:39,767
We were able to extract it

848
00:34:39,800 --> 00:34:42,567
and her BP is now 128/90.

849
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:45,867
Heart rate's 70.
Vital signs all appear normal.

850
00:34:45,900 --> 00:34:49,200
‐ You mean she's not dead?
‐ No, no. She's not dead.

851
00:34:49,233 --> 00:34:51,267
She's asleep,
but definitely not dead.

852
00:34:51,300 --> 00:34:52,533
Can we see her?

853
00:34:52,567 --> 00:34:54,233
Like I said,
she's asleep, so..

854
00:34:57,633 --> 00:35:00,333
Dr. Lee?
I'm really sorry.

855
00:35:00,367 --> 00:35:02,267
We looked everywhere and we
couldn't find your earring.

856
00:35:02,300 --> 00:35:05,200
Oh. Well, thank you
anyway for looking.

857
00:35:05,233 --> 00:35:06,567
Did you lose an earring?

858
00:35:06,600 --> 00:35:09,867
Yes. Not expensive or anything.

859
00:35:09,900 --> 00:35:12,600
‐ Sentimental value.
‐ Oh?

860
00:35:12,633 --> 00:35:15,300
‐ Yes, I was engaged once.
‐ Hmm.

861
00:35:15,333 --> 00:35:17,700
To a really lovely
man, and he was killed

862
00:35:17,733 --> 00:35:22,300
in a freak horseback
riding accident.

863
00:35:22,333 --> 00:35:25,800
Actually, we were on a bridge,
and the horse spooked and..

864
00:35:27,667 --> 00:35:29,733
‐ Oh.
‐ Anyway, he gave them to me.

865
00:35:29,767 --> 00:35:32,400
I'm so sorry.

866
00:35:32,433 --> 00:35:34,233
It was a long time ago.

867
00:36:00,467 --> 00:36:03,133
Yeah. David Kotlowitz, please.

868
00:36:03,167 --> 00:36:04,200
Peter Benton.

869
00:36:04,233 --> 00:36:05,300
Hey, David. Hey.

870
00:36:05,333 --> 00:36:07,833
Uh, listen, I, um..

871
00:36:07,867 --> 00:36:11,333
I wanted to postpone
Reese's operation.

872
00:36:11,367 --> 00:36:14,300
Well, I mean, you know, he's
barely within the age range

873
00:36:14,333 --> 00:36:16,367
and he's got a fair
amount of residual hearing

874
00:36:16,400 --> 00:36:17,733
and the technology's
changing all the time.

875
00:36:17,767 --> 00:36:19,767
I just, you know..

876
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:21,433
No, yeah. I‐I just saw him.

877
00:36:21,467 --> 00:36:23,733
He's.. He's doing fine.

878
00:36:23,767 --> 00:36:25,633
Mm‐hmm.

879
00:36:25,667 --> 00:36:28,833
Yeah, well, uh, you, too.

880
00:36:28,867 --> 00:36:30,367
Have a great holiday, alright?

881
00:36:32,700 --> 00:36:34,467
My parents called on
the way from the airport.

882
00:36:37,567 --> 00:36:39,167
My dad has a phone in his car.

883
00:36:45,433 --> 00:36:47,700
You're mad at me about
something, aren't you?

884
00:36:48,300 --> 00:36:49,833
No.

885
00:36:49,867 --> 00:36:51,433
When my mom gets
mad she just stands

886
00:36:51,467 --> 00:36:53,333
at the kitchen
sink and does dishes

887
00:36:53,367 --> 00:36:56,300
and she doesn't say anything.

888
00:36:56,333 --> 00:36:57,733
I'm not mad, Wilson.

889
00:36:57,767 --> 00:37:00,733
I'm sad about
what happened to Andy.

890
00:37:00,767 --> 00:37:03,500
I mean it's so cool if he was
in one of these other beds.

891
00:37:06,267 --> 00:37:08,500
Do you know what
it means to be sad?

892
00:37:11,567 --> 00:37:12,833
Wilson, do you
know what it means

893
00:37:12,867 --> 00:37:14,733
to have done something wrong?

894
00:37:21,300 --> 00:37:23,700
Carol, his parents are here.

895
00:37:24,600 --> 00:37:25,667
Thanks, Connie.

896
00:37:47,500 --> 00:37:48,800
What, you waiting on a bus?

897
00:37:50,800 --> 00:37:53,333
I wish I was on
a bus going anywhere.

898
00:37:53,367 --> 00:37:56,233
Oh. How'd it go
with Anspaugh?

899
00:37:56,267 --> 00:37:58,733
Ah, well,
no crime, no punishment.

900
00:37:58,767 --> 00:38:00,467
Seems what I did
wasn't terribly wrong

901
00:38:00,500 --> 00:38:02,167
therefore no need
to penalize me

902
00:38:02,200 --> 00:38:03,633
therefore no need
to examine a system

903
00:38:03,667 --> 00:38:06,400
that has served so many
so well for so long.

904
00:38:06,433 --> 00:38:08,400
Yeah, they seemed
pretty shocked

905
00:38:08,433 --> 00:38:09,700
that you actually suggested it.

906
00:38:12,167 --> 00:38:13,700
As were you.

907
00:38:13,733 --> 00:38:16,367
Yeah, well, it wouldn't
have been my choice.

908
00:38:19,500 --> 00:38:22,367
Well, you and I never make
the same choices, do we?

909
00:38:24,800 --> 00:38:25,767
No.

910
00:38:27,667 --> 00:38:31,400
Well, Peter, we could now.

911
00:38:31,433 --> 00:38:33,700
Come on, Peter.
This should be over.

912
00:38:33,733 --> 00:38:35,500
I mean some would
argue that it already is.

913
00:38:35,533 --> 00:38:37,733
We haven't been alone
together for weeks.

914
00:38:39,733 --> 00:38:42,133
I need to focus
on my son right now.

915
00:38:42,167 --> 00:38:45,100
Look we could both draw up
a list of reasons why

916
00:38:45,133 --> 00:38:48,533
but why don't we just put it
down to faulty construction?

917
00:38:48,567 --> 00:38:52,833
A casual relationship has to
grow into something or it dies.

918
00:38:52,867 --> 00:38:54,700
Well, it's not like I
haven't wanted to see it grow.

919
00:38:54,733 --> 00:38:57,700
It's just that I..

920
00:38:57,733 --> 00:39:00,733
...I don't have it
to give right now. I..

921
00:39:00,767 --> 00:39:02,233
Yeah.

922
00:39:02,267 --> 00:39:03,800
I understand that.

923
00:39:05,533 --> 00:39:08,067
Which is why I think
maybe, um..

924
00:39:10,200 --> 00:39:12,133
...we'll be better
off as friends.

925
00:39:20,167 --> 00:39:21,733
‐ I'll see you around, okay?
‐ Okay.

926
00:39:24,600 --> 00:39:26,100
Now, you probably
didn't know it

927
00:39:26,133 --> 00:39:28,300
but we've been
off work for 20 minutes.

928
00:39:28,333 --> 00:39:29,467
Get something to eat?

929
00:39:29,500 --> 00:39:32,333
Maybe Rosebud
or Morton's, Johnny D's?

930
00:39:32,367 --> 00:39:33,500
Home, bathtub, bed.

931
00:39:33,533 --> 00:39:34,667
That's my girl.

932
00:39:35,767 --> 00:39:38,100
I met them today, you know.

933
00:39:38,133 --> 00:39:41,200
Seemed like
perfectly normal people.

934
00:39:41,233 --> 00:39:43,367
Father's a sales rep,
office supplies.

935
00:39:43,400 --> 00:39:44,733
Mother went to
Dallas with him

936
00:39:44,767 --> 00:39:46,833
'cause she wanted to
visit her favorite aunt.

937
00:39:46,867 --> 00:39:48,667
Wilson's parents?

938
00:39:48,700 --> 00:39:50,200
Thought they'd
have to be monsters

939
00:39:50,233 --> 00:39:52,267
to raise a kid who could
do something like that.

940
00:39:52,300 --> 00:39:54,433
Well, that would explain
everything, wouldn't it?

941
00:39:54,467 --> 00:39:57,700
Parents beat the kid,
or they yell at him

942
00:39:57,733 --> 00:40:00,300
or starve him so he ends up
killing his best friend.

943
00:40:01,500 --> 00:40:03,867
Then why did he do it?

944
00:40:03,900 --> 00:40:05,267
Stuff happens.

945
00:40:07,300 --> 00:40:08,867
An eight‐year‐old shoots
another eight‐year‐old

946
00:40:08,900 --> 00:40:11,633
and you say stuff happens?

947
00:40:11,667 --> 00:40:13,433
You got a better answer?

948
00:40:13,467 --> 00:40:16,533
No. No, I don't.
I don't know.

949
00:40:16,567 --> 00:40:19,533
Maybe his genes
are screwy or..

950
00:40:19,567 --> 00:40:21,767
...his parents seem nice, but
they ignore him. I don't know.

951
00:40:21,800 --> 00:40:23,267
Maybe he plays
too many video games

952
00:40:23,300 --> 00:40:25,267
like every kid in America.
It's..

953
00:40:27,533 --> 00:40:30,233
Doesn't it bother you
that there isn't any reason?

954
00:40:31,567 --> 00:40:34,367
No, it bothers me
that you cared about him

955
00:40:34,400 --> 00:40:38,333
and you believed in him,
and now you feel betrayed.

956
00:40:38,367 --> 00:40:39,467
I don't feel betrayed.

957
00:40:39,500 --> 00:40:42,067
I feel...scared.

958
00:40:43,833 --> 00:40:45,367
I mean, if you don't
know what causes it

959
00:40:45,400 --> 00:40:48,100
how do you keep
it from happening?

960
00:40:48,133 --> 00:40:49,833
Are we any different
from that couple?

961
00:40:49,867 --> 00:40:53,633
They didn't see it coming.
Would we see it coming?

962
00:40:53,667 --> 00:40:56,433
Yeah, you bring a child
into this world

963
00:40:56,467 --> 00:40:57,533
and you think that
they're helpless

964
00:40:57,567 --> 00:41:00,667
but actually,
I think it's us.

965
00:41:00,700 --> 00:41:01,867
I think we're the ones
that are helpless.

966
00:41:01,900 --> 00:41:04,100
We probably are but..

967
00:41:04,133 --> 00:41:06,700
And that's why you
love them as much as you can

968
00:41:06,733 --> 00:41:09,567
and you teach
them as best you can

969
00:41:11,567 --> 00:41:14,100
and then you
wish them good luck.

970
00:41:20,033 --> 00:41:22,666
What do you say?

971
00:41:22,699 --> 00:41:25,866
Home, bath, bed?

972
00:41:30,099 --> 00:41:31,233
Hmm?

973
00:41:33,166 --> 00:41:35,699
‐ Yeah.
‐ Yeah.

974
00:41:41,149 --> 00:41:42,782
I mean you know
if you don't have any plans

975
00:41:42,816 --> 00:41:44,416
if you're not busy.

976
00:41:44,449 --> 00:41:46,649
Having a drink sounds great.
Can we also eat something?

977
00:41:46,682 --> 00:41:48,082
‐ Dinner, absolutely.
‐ Okay.

978
00:41:48,116 --> 00:41:49,216
I have a meeting
with Anspaugh

979
00:41:49,249 --> 00:41:50,582
for about 20
then I'll be right back.

980
00:41:50,616 --> 00:41:52,049
‐ Sounds great.
‐ Buddy, we're going home.

981
00:41:52,082 --> 00:41:53,082
What's your story?

982
00:41:53,116 --> 00:41:54,249
Ah, catching up on paperwork.

983
00:41:54,282 --> 00:41:55,616
Well, curfew's at 11:00.

984
00:41:55,649 --> 00:41:57,082
Ha, ha, ha.
Very funny.

985
00:42:03,840 --> 00:42:04,840
ER.

986
00:42:05,973 --> 00:42:07,073
How about this snow?

987
00:42:07,106 --> 00:42:08,273
Yeah, it's pretty great, huh?

988
00:42:08,306 --> 00:42:09,973
‐ Have a good shift.
‐ 'Always.'

989
00:42:10,006 --> 00:42:11,340
Whoa, you got to help me.
My wife's having a baby!

990
00:42:11,373 --> 00:42:13,073
What?

991
00:42:13,106 --> 00:42:14,073
Huh?

992
00:42:15,873 --> 00:42:17,406
Hang on, hang on.

993
00:42:17,440 --> 00:42:19,106
We're not due
for two more weeks.

994
00:42:20,173 --> 00:42:21,373
Somebody lied.

995
00:42:21,406 --> 00:42:23,040
Oh, God, Louis,
help me. Help me!

996
00:42:23,073 --> 00:42:24,373
We're gonna help you.
We're gonna help you.

997
00:42:24,406 --> 00:42:26,140
‐ Okay, get Mark and a gurney.
‐ Yeah.

998
00:42:26,173 --> 00:42:27,973
‐ Do something, please.
‐ Ma'am, ma'am, I'm a doctor.

999
00:42:32,306 --> 00:42:34,806
Alright, alright, I got it.

1000
00:42:34,840 --> 00:42:36,706
Bring her up.

1001
00:42:36,740 --> 00:42:38,206
Good. You know how to breathe.

1002
00:42:38,240 --> 00:42:40,273
‐ This is our fourth.
‐ Then I guess it's coming.

1003
00:42:40,306 --> 00:42:43,140
‐ When did it start snowing?
‐ Crowning.

1004
00:42:43,173 --> 00:42:44,773
We're not due
for two more weeks.

1005
00:42:44,806 --> 00:42:46,806
‐ It must be all the excitement.
‐ What's your name?

1006
00:42:46,840 --> 00:42:48,840
I'm Louis, Louis Bernucci.
This is my wife Gilda.

1007
00:42:48,873 --> 00:42:51,006
Hi, Gilda, nice to meet you.
You ready to push?

1008
00:42:51,040 --> 00:42:53,006
On the next one,
I want you to push, okay?

1009
00:42:53,040 --> 00:42:55,373
Ready, and one, two, three.
Push!

1010
00:42:55,406 --> 00:42:57,173
God!

1011
00:43:00,173 --> 00:43:03,173
If it's a girl,
I wanna name it after nana.

1012
00:43:03,206 --> 00:43:04,973
Ruth?

1013
00:43:05,006 --> 00:43:06,206
Ruth Johnson.

